80–1142":"1080–1142","–Female":"Deceased","1120–1161":"1120–1161","1123–Male":"1123–Deceased","1030–1100":"1030–1100","1080":"1080","about 1080":"about 1080","1165":"1165","1142":"1142","1120":"1120","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1030":"1030","1161":"1161","1071":"1071","1106":"1106","1123":"1123","1100":"1100","before 1120":"before 1120","about 1123":"about 1123","about 1120":"about 1120","Wychnor, Staffordshire, England":"Wychnor, Staffordshire, England","Europe":"Europe","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Somerville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Graveron-Sémerville in Eure (Normandy), from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sigimar</i> (see   Siemer  ) + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. The surname was taken to Scotland in the 12th century by William <i>de Somerville</i>, a retainer of David, Earl of Huntingdon, who became King David I of Scotland.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Somacháin</b> (see   Summers  ) or <b>Mag Shamradháin</b> (see   Somers  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Siemer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Helmuth, Otto, Theresia.","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Siegmar</i>, composed of the elements <i>sigi</i> ‘victory’ + <i>mari</i>, <i>meri</i> ‘famous’."]},{"name":"Sommerville","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire): variant of   Somerville   1."]},{"name":"Summerville","meanings":["English, Scottish (Lanarkshire), and Irish: variant of   Somerville  . This form of the surname is particularly common in Ireland."]},{"name":"Simrell","meanings":["Scottish: perhaps related to the Ulster name<b>Sumeril</b>, a variant of   Somerville  ."]},{"name":"Summerfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>sumor</i> ‘summer’ + <i>feld</i> ‘field, open land’, denoting summer pasture or fields cultivated only in summer, such as Summerfield in Woodnesborough (Kent), Somerfield Court in Sellindge (Kent), and Summerfield in Marlborough (Wiltshire).","English: variant of   Somerville  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Sommerfeld  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":6,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":16,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":26,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William de Somerville was born about 1080, in Wychnor, Staffordshire, England as the son of Gaulter Somerville. He married wife William de Somerville before 1120, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1142, in Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland, at the age of 63."},"et":{"about 1080–1142":"umbes 1080–1142","1071–1165":"1071–1165","1080–1142":"1080–1142","–Female":"Surnud","1120–1161":"1120–1161","1123–Male":"1123–Surnud","1030–1100":"1030–1100","1080":"1080","about 1080":"umbes 1080","1165":"1165","1142":"1142","1120":"1120","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1030":"1030","1161":"1161","1071":"1071","1106":"1106","1123":"1123","1100":"1100","before 1120":"enne 1120","about 1123":"umbes 1123","about 1120":"umbes 1120","Wychnor, Staffordshire, England":"Wychnor, Staffordshire, England","Europe":"Europe","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1080–1142":"noin 1080–1142","1071–1165":"1071–1165","1080–1142":"1080–1142","–Female":"Kuollut","1120–1161":"1120–1161","1123–Male":"1123–Kuollut","1030–1100":